<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Vote eases way for Macedonia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KERIN HOPE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ATHENS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREEK government survived a censure motion in parliament yesterday on
the issue of recognising Macedonia, but Mr Constantine Mitsotakis, prime
minister, has not yet managed to quash objections by hardliners in his New
Democracy party, writes Kerin Hope in Athens. The 152-145 vote clears the
way for the government to give a positive response to a UN Security Council
resolution that calls for admitting Macedonia to the UN under a temporary
name, pending international arbitration between Athens and Skopje on a
permanent one.
However, dissension remains in the party ranks underlined by the decision of
Mr George Rallis, a former prime minster, to resign his parliamentary seat
in protest at the government's handling of the question. The government also
appears to have last-minute worries that if it accepts the UN resolution,
the Macedonian flag, carrying an ancient Greek emblem, will be immediately
raised outside the UN building in New York. Changes to the flag is an issue
to be decided by UN arbitration.
</TEXT>
