<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (27): A basic guide for the visitor -
Contacts are usually readily accessible - but make appointments before you
travel, urges Bob Baker / Contacts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BOB BAKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Communicating with contacts in Guernsey, from almost any part of the world,
is relatively straight forward by international subscriber dialling,
facsimile or telex. The island's telecommunications are run by Guernsey
Telecoms, an autonomous trading department of the insular government that
has its own local directory inquiry service.
From the UK and Jersey, calls to Guernsey, Alderney, Sark and Herm need the
prefix code 0481 and international calls need the code 44 481.
Inward postal, freight and courier services are reliable with rapid delivery
times on the island. The Bailiwick of Guernsey's postal services have been
run since 1969 by the Guernsey Post Office, another autonomous trading
department of the insular government.
There are regular scheduled air passenger services into Guernsey from not
only Heathrow, Stansted, Gatwick and Southampton - with flying times of
under an hour - but also from other UK regional airports and several
European airports.
A conventional, roll-on, roll-off passenger/car ferry service operates
between Guernsey and Poole but the fastest scheduled crossings - 2 1/4 hours
 -are from Weymouth by high-speed passenger ferries including a new
passenger/car 'wave-piercing' catamaran. There are also various sea
transport links into Guernsey from Jersey, Alderney, Sark, Cherbourg and St
Malo.
It is sensible to make prior appointments with contacts in Guernsey before
travelling to the island and to be aware that scheduled air services can be
disrupted from time to time by fog.
Visitors travelling by sea will arrive at St Peter Port Harbour just a short
walk or road journey from any St Peter Port destination. For those arriving
by air there is bus service or a 20-minute car journey into town.
Contacts are usually readily accessible, partly because the island is small.
A leisurely drive around most of Guernsey along the coast roads takes only
about 45 minutes - even when cruising below the maximum speed limit of
35mph.
The Guernsey telephone directory, published annually each May, is an
invaluable tool for anyone trying to contact not only individual residents
or businesses but also official and voluntary bodies.
Three pages containthe names and telephone numbers of official contacts
within island government and public administration. This list is headed by
members of The Royal Court of Guernsey, every local politician and parish
official, plus the names and addresses of all States of Guernsey
Departments.
There is a Yellow Pages section at the end of the directory. In addition,
there is a section explaining the island's public warning systems in the
event of big disasters or emergencies, including nuclear accidents. Guernsey
The Queen's Representative in Guernsey and Commander-in-Chief of the
Bailiwick and its Dependencies is His Excellency the Lieutenant-Governor,
Lt-General Sir Michael Wilkins, Government House, The Queen's Road, St Peter
Port.
His Secretary and ADC is Captain David Hodgetts, of the same address.
Telephone 726666.
The civil head of Guernsey, also the head of the legislature and judiciary
is The Bailiff, Mr G. M. Dorey, The Bailiff's Chambers, The Royal Court
House, St Peter Port.
The Deputy Bailiff is Mr de V. G. Carey of the same address which is also
the address of the Bailiff's Secretary, Mr A. E. Richings. Telephone 726161.
Fax 713861.
The Procureur (Attorney-General) is Mr A. K. Day, St James Chambers, St
Peter Port, which is also the office of the Comptroller (Solicitor-General),
Mr G. R. Rowland. Telephone 723355.
The Greffier (Keeper of Court and Public Records) is Mr Ken Tough, Greffe,
Royal Court House, St Peter Port. Telephone 725277.
The lead committee of the States of Guernsey is the Advisory and Finance
Committee. Its address is Sir Charles Frossard House, Charroterie, St Peter
Port. Telephone: 717000.
The same address and telephone number apply for:
Conseiller Roydon Falla, president of the Advisory and Finance Committee,
(the Island's 'chancellor of the exchequer') and ex officio chairman of the
Guernsey Financial Services Commission.
Mr M. J. Brown, States Supervisor, the head of the civil service.
Mr R. Trestain, States Treasurer; Mr G. Sauvage, Policy Analyst; and Mr J.
Dickson, head of Economics and Statistics Department.
The President of the Guernsey Board of Industry is Mr David Evans, States
Offices, Burnt Lane, St Martin's, Guernsey, whose senior executives are Mr
Bob Bartlett and Mr Tony Brassell of the same address. Telephone 35741. Fax
35015.
The President of the Guernsey Tourist Board is Conseiller Richard Ozanne,
Cambridge Berth, St Peter Port. The same address applies for Mr Michael
Walden, Director of Tourism; Mr Evan Ozanne, Deputy Director of Tourism; and
Mr Tim Orton, Conferences Officer. Telephone 726611, Fax 721246.
The director-general of the Guernsey Financial Services Commission is Mr
John Roper, Valley House, Hirzel Street, St Peter Port. This address also
applies for Mr Peter Crook, Superintendent of Banking; Mr Nigel Taylor,
Superintendent of Investment Business; and Mr Steve Butterworth,
Superintendent of Insurance. Telephone 712706, Fax 712010.
The chairman of the Guernsey International Business Association, which
represents all sectors of the Island's financial services industry, is Mr
Bruce Riley, managing director of Guinness Flight Fund Managers (Guernsey)
of PO Box 250, La Plaiderie, St Peter Port. Telephone 712176. Fax 712065.
His deputy is Mr Denham Chaloner, managing director, Bank of Bermuda
(Guernsey), PO Box 208, St Julian's Avenue, St Peter Port. Telephone 726268,
Fax 726987.
The chief officer of the Guernsey Police Force is Mr Michael Le Moignan of
Police Headquarters, Amherst, St Peter Port. Telephone 25111.
The Guernsey Chamber of Commerce is at States Arcade, Market Square, St
Peter Port. Telephone 727483. Fax 710755.
The Guernsey Hotel and Tourism Association is also based at States Arcade,
Market Square, St Peter Port. Telephone 722533.
The States of Guernsey Tourist Information Centre and Accommodation Service
is at Crown Pier, St Peter Port. Telephone 723555.
Alderney
The president of the States of Alderney is Mr Jon Kay-Mouat, States Office,
New Street, St Anne's. Telephone 822811.
Sark
The Seigneur of Sark is Mr Michael Beaumont, La Seigneurie, Sark. Telephone
832017.
</TEXT>
