<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (20): Norman French titles and roles -
Richard Evans takes a look at a system that has survived the centuries
remarkably intact / Profile: The bailiff
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN the UK, the title bailiff has been debased to mean the repossessor of a
debtor's goods, but in Guernsey it has retained its original meaning of the
sovereign's representative in a district.
The bailiff is the equivalent of the lord chancellor, presiding over the
royal court and the legislature and heading the island's administration.
Given that Guernsey, like Jersey and the Isle of Man, is a virtually
independent democracy in domestic affairs, it is a post of the greatest
local importance.
Lists on the walls of the spacious, panelled offices of the current bailiff,
Mr Graham Dorey, show an unbroken line of bailiffs going back to William de
Saint Remy in 1278 - and the office existed before then.
The island, with neighbouring Jersey, was integrated into the Duchy of
Normandy in the 10th and 11th centuries and became a dependent territory of
the English crown when the duke, William, became king of England in 1066.
When continental Normandy was overrun by the king of France in 1204, the
islands remained under the English king, who continued to govern them in his
capacity as duke of Normandy.
The rule continued after the title was dropped.
Their separate laws, customs and liberties were later confirmed by the
charters of successive sovereigns, which secured the islands their own
judiciaries, freedom from the processes of the English courts, and certain
other privileges.
The office of bailiff is at the apex of a system that has survived the
centuries remarkably intact and has retained many of the original Norman
French titles and roles. Ironically, these were largely abolished in
Normandy itself at the time of the French revolution.
In some respects, such as inheritance, bankruptcy and family legislation,
local law still differs considerably from that in the UK. Most criminal and
commercial law has come increasingly into line, though.
Mr Dorey, like all recent incumbents, is a Guernseyman and a lawyer. He has
been in office for just over a year, having climbed the ranks of the law
officers appointed by the British crown of comptroller (or
solicitor-general), procureur (attorney-general) and deputy bailiff, an
office created in 1969 because of the increasing work load.
Before that, Mr Dorey was in private practice as a Guernsey advocate, having
gone through the obligatory process of a six-month course at Caen university
to study Norman law as well as qualifying at the English Bar.
He does not believe there is any conflict of interest between the judicial
and administrative functions of the office. 'There could be in theory, but
if we see one in prospect we head it off. I would avoid it by not sitting in
court, for example. My place could be taken by my deputy or by a judge from
the English court of appeal.'
One of the bailiff's tasks is to head deputations from the States - the
local parliament - to the Home Office, which is responsible for relations
between the UK and the Channel Islands, on any conflict or concern. The only
significant delegation recently was over French fishing rights at the Schole
Bank off the island. This had been a matter of dispute for 20 years but
after visits to London and Paris the matter was resolved.
A much less easily resolved matter has been the sensitive issue of Guernsey
and the German occupation from 1940 to 1945. Mr Dorey has played a prominent
part in refuting allegations of wholesale collaboration and black
marketeering by islanders that appeared when records were opened for
inspection early this year.
'A lot of extremely offensive and false material was circulated and there
has been a great deal of misunderstanding. . . our files show that at the
express instruction of the British government the island authorities
remained in being and acted as a buffer against the Germans on behalf of the
small remaining population.
'Refusal (to obey German orders) was not possible as to do so would only
have brought reprisals on a defenceless population,' Mr Dorey said.
The Dorey family has lived on Guernsey for about 400 years, but although
forebears have been deputies and jurats - the 12 elected people who in
effect constitute a permanent jury - none has been bailiff before.
Mr Dorey acknowledges there is a belief that Guernsey is dominated by seven
extended families, but he is adamant that this does not affect the choice of
bailiff.
'It is a delicate subject, but it is quite false to say the role only goes
to old families. The position is open to all.' He estimates that out of the
past nine bailiffs, only two came from families which had previously filled
the post, although the position was very different in the last century and
before.
</TEXT>
<XX>
