<DATE>930331
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (9): Housing controls prevent an influx -
Property
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The attractions of Guernsey as a place to live and work, with its regulatory
independence, low tax rates and a pleasant climate, have led to strict
controls over the island's housing market to prevent mass immigration from
the UK.
It became clear soon after the Second World War that without some form of
control over the occupation of residential properties, prices would escalate
out of reach of the local population.
In 1948 the States, or local legislature, foresaw future problems and
introduced a housing control law in a relatively mild form.
This has since been amended and strengthened many times and it is now
regarded as a highly effective barrier against an influx of outsiders.
The island's 18,000 homes have been divided into two categories, with 90 per
cent available for occupancy only by the local population - broadly those
born in Guernsey or with Guernsey parents - and the remaining 10 per cent
designated as 'open market' housing which anyone can buy and occupy.
The only exceptions are those outsiders granted a housing licence by the
local authority to occupy local homes, but these are given infrequently and
generally only to people with job skills and qualifications that cannot be
provided locally.
Open-market housing, which was originally chosen because of its relatively
high rateable value, is generally the larger executive type of house, and
the number is fixed.
No transfer into the open market category is allowed, and no new building
plots are available.
In such a restricted market and given the pressures that have followed the
influx of highly paid executives in the financial services sector, prices
have stayed high.
According to Mr John Allen, managing director of Swoffers, a local estate
agents, open-market prices climbed to 'dizzy heights' prior to the
recession, with Pounds 2m the highest price achieved. But since the end of
1990, prices have retreated by about 25 per cent as potential buyers from
the UK have had difficulties selling their homes and businesses.
The base level for a modest open-market semi-detached house has fallen from
Pounds 200,000 to Pounds 175,000 or even Pounds 150,000, and an old
farmhouse in 10 acres and in good condition would now fetch between Pounds
650,000 and Pounds 800,000.
Prices have also fallen on the local market as the recession has taken
effect, but not nearly to the same extent. 'They have been bumping along
rather than falling sharply,' says Mr Allen.
In general, open-market houses fetch between two and three times their local
equivalent, where the asking prices are around Pounds 90,000 to Pounds
100,000 for an average three-bedroom semi and Pounds 60,000 for a base-level
two-bedroom terrace house.
There are now probably between 150 and 200 open-market houses up for sale -
a relatively high number given that there were only 60 transactions
completed in each of the past two years, compared with 120 in 1989.
One problem has been that owners are reluctant to cut prices that still hark
back to the levels of two years ago.
Mr Ben Lovell, of Lovell &amp; Partners in St Peter Port, believes the local
market has begun to improve significantly, and is much more buoyant than
just six months ago. 'We are lucky. When the recession hits the UK, it
affects us later and not so sharply.'
However, he accepts that neither the open nor the local market will recover
fully until the UK housing and business sectors improve substantially.
Mr Lovell believes Guernsey's unique system works well. 'It is very
straightforward and uncomplicated.'
Because the restricted supply keeps open-market values high, the signs of a
relatively good value local market might tempt incomers to dodge the island
rules. In practice, tighter employment laws would exclude such buyers from
the jobs market.
In addition, the island is too small a community to try bending the
regulations, especially as the completion of any property transaction has to
take place in the royal court in front of the bailiff. It is a public
transaction, rather than a discreet transfer of deeds.
Relatively few licences are granted for outsiders to buy local properties,
but there is growing pressure on the housing authority to be more liberal in
its judgments, particularly over short-term licences for key personnel in
the hotel and restaurant sector.
More homes are planned for locals, almost entirely in carefully designated
built-up zones, in order to prevent more building in rural areas.
Alderney and Sark do not have housing controls but property can be scarce
and expensive. Alderney operates a work permit system, but it is very
flexible and insists simply that incomers have no criminal record.
</TEXT>
