<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (6): End to recession will bring growth -
Guernsey has advantages for long-term contracts such as a retirement pension
/ Pensions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GUERNSEY has been trying to capture a sizeable slice of the market in
off-shore pensions, but although a range of products is now in place,
success has been patchy.
The target market is the expatriate employee or third-country national who
works in a number of countries or who finds it impractical or impossible for
tax reasons to fund a retirement policy in his or her own country.
It is a market which grew rapidly throughout the 1980s and although it has
been badly affected by the world recession it could be set to expand
substantially during the 1990s.
Two broad types of international pensions products are marketed in Guernsey:
international personal pensions or retirement annuities aimed at
individuals; and off-shore pensions targeted at companies to establish for
their employees. Guernsey-based insurance companies tend to specialise in
one or the other.
According to Mr Rodney Benjamin, a Guernsey partner in consulting actuaries
Bacon &amp; Woodrow, some of the schemes could also be of interest to capped
executives in the UK where there is no tax advantage for pensions on
earnings over Pounds 75,000. 'These are now being marketed quite actively
and as the UK claws its way out of recession and the cap bites more deeply,
interest should increase,' he said.
There are certain clear advantages for choosing Guernsey for a long-term
contract such as a retirement pension. According to a recent survey of
clients conducted by the Guernsey branch of Generali, the Trieste-based
international insurance conglomerate, top of the list is political
stability, which has been a big factor in the island's success as a
financial centre.
This is followed by its fiscal independence - Guernsey is responsible for
its own domestic affairs, including taxation, and is not subject to
harmonisation of European Community taxation; excellent communications; and
a sophisticated infrastructure which provides the back-up services of
lawyers, accountants, actuaries and other specialists.
For off-shore insurers, policyholders' funds are free of Guernsey taxation,
thus the income and capital gains accruing on the funds are not taxed and no
tax is imposed when payments are made. Guernsey also has specific
legislation for the establishment of pension fund trusts.
However, despite these inherent advantages, progress has been
disappointingly slow, partly because of a flying start by neighbouring
Jersey which soaked up much of the early business.
Both islands produced similar concepts for expatriate and off-shore pensions
but Jersey was able to put its proposals through much more rapidly because
it does not need Privy Council approval as does Guernsey.
Guernsey's legislation was also part of a package which included local
pensions provisions and this delayed implementation for a year.
Jersey passed its so-called Article 131(C) pension plan legislation in 1990
and Norwich Union, the market leader, and other insurers achieved an early
start. Guernsey's Section 40 (ee) for personal pensions and Section 40 (O)
for organisations did not come into operation until 18 months ago, and
Guernsey-based companies have had problems catching up.
Although broadly similar, there are subtle differences in approach between
the two islands. Both want to ensure they gain revenue benefits from the
products channelled through them, but whereas Jersey has provided that the
pension plans must be sold through a resident insurance broker, Guernsey has
imposed no such requirement.
The difference is largely explained by the fact that Jersey has no life
assurance companies of its own, whereas Guernsey has several including
Providence Capitol International, Sun Alliance International and Nordben,
all incorporated in Guernsey, and Generali and Equitable Life, which are
branch operations.
A branch selling Article 131(C) business in Jersey is exempt from tax,
whereas an operation in Guernsey is liable to tax on its profits but at the
low rate of 20 per cent, and for a non-resident company this can be offset
against tax levied elsewhere. In addition, the income tax authorities have
specifically excluded the sale of Article 131(C) contracts to UK residents,
but Guernsey does not exclude this possibility.
Offshore pension contracts are much more flexible than their onshore
equivalents in aspects such as retirement age, cash commutation, or the form
in which benefits are received in retirement, and they are not constrained
by tax legislation.
Providence Capitol, probably the biggest local insurer with a staff of 75,
has developed a flexible international personal pension plan. Others are
thinking of following.
Mr Mel Carvill, Guernsey branch manager for Generali which specialises in
offshore pensions for multinational companies and for international
organisations such as the United Nations, also emphasises the flexibility
that local plans give, including scope to transfer funds to the UK or
elsewhere to buy an annuity on retirement. 'Our growth in Guernsey has been
significant,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
