<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (5): Leading the field with its captives
 -Guernsey is the largest centre in Europe and one of the biggest in the
world after locations such as Bermuda and the Caymans / Insurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF there is one category of financial services in which Guernsey has
out-performed its rival offshore centres, it is in the cultivation of
captive insurance companies.
Banks and other institutions have gained a foothold as in many offshore
centres. But few can compete with Guernsey's status on captives, and
certainly not Jersey, its most obvious rival, which only recently offered
rapprochement to insurance companies.
'We had a captive market for captives,' says Mr Bruce Riley, industry
supervisor during the 1970s and early 1980s when much of the growth took
place and who is now managing director of Guinness Flight Fund Managers in
Guernsey.
The total number of captives is now 230 - making Guernsey the largest centre
in Europe and one of the biggest in the world, after locations such as
Bermuda and the Cayman Islands. Guernsey had the largest number of net new
captives last year.
Much of the expansion came in the early 1970s. The contraction of the
sterling area left the Channel Islands in a privileged position within the
boundaries, at a time when the insurance market was hardening. As the
reputation built up, new captives arrived.
'It's really taken off in the last 15 years,' says Mr Nick Wild, director
and general manager of International Risk Management, which now manages some
17 captives on the island.
Until 1986, there was no insurance law in Guernsey. That changed with the
impetus given by the creation of the Financial Services Commission and the
appointment of Mr Steve Butterworth as superintendent of insurance.
The legislation did not help the industry. Insurance companies which had
been resident offshore from Guernsey were required to come onshore, partly
so that they could be effectively regulated.
But the effect was also to remove their tax-exempt status, at a time when
the Isle of Man was beginning to be aggressive in courting insurance
business. As a result, the number of new captives remained stable at about
18 a year.
More recent modifications in response mean that insurance companies have the
option of paying no tax, tax on a sliding scale between 0.5 per cent and 30
per cent, or paying 20 per cent. In 1992, the number of new captives rose
correspondingly to 27.
That change in policy reflects the flexibility shown by the authorities in
encouraging offshore business.
The Financial Services Commission plays a dual role, both regulating and
marketing the industry. This is borne out by Mr Butterworth's recent help in
lobbying for Guernsey captives to be included in Pool Re, the reinsurance
pool being designed to underwrite UK terrorist damage.
'If we have a problem, I can call Steve Butterworth and chat it through,'
says Mr Wild. 'With the Department of Trade and Industry you would have to
wait six months for an appointment to speak to somebody.'
He adds that the DTI also requires substantial capitalisation which is
geared far more to third-party insurers than it is to captives.
Accessibility is one reason why captives are tempted to offshore centres
such as Guernsey, Mr Wild says. To the Inland Revenue, companies with
captives are almost inevitably a subject for investigation. 'People don't
understand how captives work,' he says.
He stresses that captives are created for commercial rather than tax reasons
 -although tax rates become important once the decision has been made to
form one.
Guernsey has succeeded, Mr Wild says, because of the infrastructure of
sympathetic regulators, insurance managers and bankers, accountants and
lawyers who understand the industry.
'1992 was a very good year and 1993 is already very good,' he says. 'The
traditional UK insurance market is in disarray and premiums are rising.
'Companies are seeking greater flexibility and are more interested in
forming captives to have better control over their own destiny. They are
dusting off their feasibility studies.'
That is a view shared by Mr Granville de Cruz, managing director of
Sedgwick. 'We continue to see growth,' he says.
Regulation of captives appears to be low-key. Mr Butterworth reflects the
FSC's line of keeping out undesirable companies in the first place. One
company is currently under investigation, while he rejected six captives
last year.
Mr Butterworth is more active in other areas. He is drafting a new insurance
law. He wants new powers, including the ability to freeze assets.
For dealing with a wide variety of everyday complaints from the public, he
would like to see the creation of a financial services ombudsman.
And to deal with the sale of offshore insurance products, he is considering
a regulatory system that would require Guernsey insurers to supervise their
intermediaries and de-license any which fail to perform satisfactorily.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P63   Insurance Carriers.
    P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>COMP  Company News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
