London Page VI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT931-43</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-DC4CXAHNFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930331
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (4): Crucial role in the local economy -
At the latest count, 76 institutions held funds on deposit totalling Pounds
27bn, / Banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FROM a distance, St Julian's Avenue in St Peter Port, Guernsey, looks like a
main road near the centre of any British town. Close up, there is one vital
difference which highlights the crucial role of banking to the local
economy.
It is the names above the entrances of the modern offices gleaming with
brass nameplates. Almost without interruption, there are signs for Baring
Brothers, Bermuda House, NM Rothschild, Hambro House, Hamilton House and
Lazard House. In between are scattered a few accountants and law firms.
Five minutes' walk away, on the other side of the town, is an even more
recent and potent symbol of the astonishing concentration of banks on the
island. On the harbour front are the newly-completed, low-rise,
granite-faced offices of Credit Suisse, rumoured to have cost Pounds 10m.
Mr Roland Hurni-Gosman, the bank's managing director, has great confidence
in future business from Guernsey. Privately, he has said he intends to take
25 per cent of market share. Publicly, he says he plans to increase his 170
staff by a further 40 in the next five years, while computerisation will
increase productivity still further in the same period.
The growth of banking on Guernsey is staggering. Aside from the high street
clearers, the first banks arrived in the early 1960s, with Kleinworts, then
Rothschild and Hambros. At the latest count, there were 76 institutions
holding funds on deposit totalling some Pounds 27bn. The largest number from
a single country was the UK, but that is now just half of the total, with
many from the rest of Europe and others from across the world. There are
nine from Switzerland alone.
The recession has certainly had an impact. Several banks have left in the
past two years.
'The finance sector has not had the greatest time,' says Mr Hurni-Gosman.
'People have become more cost conscious. But we have gone one way, and
that's up.'
The same message comes from Mr Tim Betley, managing director of the Royal
Bank of Canada. 'Business is flowing in,' he says. 'One of the beauties of
this business is that the offshore game survives on uncertainties.'
The Guernsey authorities have been keen to avoid permitting the creation of
pure 'brassplate' or 'cubicle' banks which have no meaningful presence in
Guernsey. But in the past two years they have actively encouraged the
formation of 'managed' or 'administered' banks.
Bank of Bermuda, Canadian Bank of Commerce and Credit Suisse are among those
which manage a presence of other banks on their behalf. Staff will answer
one set of phones in the name of their own bank and a second set in the name
of the managed bank. Some do all the work on behalf of the managed bank.
Others have a skeleton staff, while leaving the main Guernsey bank to carry
out backroom operations.
That provides a base allowing new banks a chance to sample the prospect of
operating on the islands with low overheads and less risk while they
experiment. More important from the perspective of the authorities, managed
banks provide Guernsey with extra business and additional tax revenues
without putting additional strain on the local workforce.
Regulation in Guernsey is very much in the tradition of the Bank of England,
with an emphasis on flexibility and frequent contact. The island has been
able to focus on the top end of the market and exclude other banks which it
does not like. 'We are careful who we let in,' says Mr Peter Crook, the
banking supervisor. 'New banks have got to improve our reputation.'
He says he only accepts those which are well capitalised, highly profitable
and with an international parent in the top 500 banks worldwide. He is
looking for banks which are safe, produce revenues for the island and do not
place strains on the workforce. 'We expect them to make a profit of at least
Pounds 500,000 within three years,' says Mr Crook. 'We want the maximum
profits with the minimum number of people.'
Others - which Mr Crook estimates at about six to eight a year - are
politely told that it would not be worth their while making a formal
application to operate on the island. Fear of negative publicity has so far
prevented any from pursuing their claims for admission through the courts.
Regulators are particularly proud of one bank that failed to gain entry  -
the Bank of Credit and Commerce International, which applied to open a
branch in the late 1970s. Officials turned it away as a result of knowledge
of its reputation, and lack of information on both its ownership and its
control through holding companies in the Caymans and Luxembourg.
Regulation has tightened over the years. Since the closure of Barnett
Christie in the late 1970s, the Commission has not permitted any indigenous
banks to operate in Guernsey. The only one which does not have a separate
parent is Hanson bank, backed by Lord Hanson's business empire. Tougher
capital adequacy requirements were introduced in the mid 1980s.
As a result, Mr John Roper, head of the Commission, says fresh rules - such
as a new banking law currently being discussed - are more a response to the
need to appear well-regulated than any inherent need for improvements.
</TEXT>
