<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (3): Pay-as-you-please system even suits
the tax authorities - Guernsey's flexibility over taxation is one reason for
the substantial growth of banks, investment managers and other enterprises
associated with offshore capital flows. Surprisingly, enthusiasm for
flexible and low taxes comes from tax officials as well as contributors /
Financial services
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THEY have a rather unusual variant in Guernsey of Britain's pay-as-you-earn
tax system, which helps explain the island's role as a substantial financial
centre. It could be called pay-as-you-please.
Most jurisdictions set tax rates and expect taxpayers to comply. The
authorities on Guernsey prefer to negotiate. In the latest and most blatant
example, the new international company regulations being introduced this
year allow businesses to choose to pay virtually any rate they want, from
less than 1 per cent up to 30 per cent.
That flexibility - which is only a codification of informal arrangements
practised over many years - is one reason for the substantial growth of
banks, investment managers and other enterprises associated with offshore
capital flows since the late 1960s.
Guernsey now derives more than half its tax revenue and 54 per cent of its
gross national product from the financial sector - up from a tenth in the
early 1970s. Finance is also now the largest provider of employment -
accounting for more than 15 per cent of the working population, according to
the 1991 census.
Many jobs and profits which do not relate directly to money management are
spin-offs from it. That includes most of the leading accountancy firms, many
law practices and even a firm of actuaries, not to mention the brass plaque
engravers and rubber stamp manufacturers.
Just as important, many of those travelling to the island, staying in its
hotels and dining in its restaurants come for short business trips: nearly
one-sixth of the 330,000 or so visitors last year.
Speak to companies with a presence on the island and most will make strong
approving noises about the benefits of being there - not least the low tax
rates, which even for resident local companies are just 20 per cent, the
same as for individuals. Similar words issue forth from many politicians and
civil servants.
What is more surprising is that the same enthusiasm for flexible and low
taxes also comes from tax officials. Suitably enough, the States of Guernsey
income tax office is hidden down an obscure alley and the sign marking its
presence above the entrance is faded almost beyond recognition.
From his room on the fourth floor, Mr Ken Forman, the administrator of
taxes, makes no apologies for his approach and admits he has a dual role:
part collector, part salesman. 'Our policy has to be flexible,' he says. 'It
is a price we have to pay. We want a slice of the cake. Otherwise money
would be lost to another territory.'
The same tension between regulation and marketing exists for officials at
the Financial Services Commission. The FSC was created in the mid 1980s to
be independent of government. Its chairman is the elected president of the
island's finance and advisory committee. But its four commissioners are
drawn from the finance sector, which also funds the agency. Recently these
funders have been pushing for a greater role in selecting the commissioners.
Talk to banks and other financial institutions, and there appears to be a
strong sense of camaraderie with the regulators. They refer to the
supervisors by their first names and say they can always call them or
arrange a meeting within a few hours. It is a quintessentially British
system, but on a far more intimate, workable scale.
Officials are keen to point out that Guernsey was never created as an
artificial offshore centre. Indeed, they prefer to avoid use of the word
'offshore' altogether, in favour of 'finance' centre. But a growing element
of artificiality has begun to creep in as more and more centres compete in
an international beauty parade for business. Legislators and regulators are
being forced to look over their shoulders more often - not least at Jersey.
Mr John Roper, head of the FSC, talks about 'a pragmatic pragmatism.' In the
UK, the authorities can all but impose their rules on most individuals and
businesses, he argues. In Guernsey, by contrast, harsh conditions will
simply drive mobile international business away.
That is not to say that every change has favoured business. Insurance
companies were forced to come onshore for regulation in 1986. More
generally, tax exemptions in the past few years have all but put an end to
the 'Sark Lark', by which companies held meetings and had directors on the
nearby island of Sark to be offshore from the Guernsey authorities.
Tougher new banking and insurance laws are planned for this year, and in the
future there are plans for the regulation of stock brokers and fiduciaries -
something not yet attempted in the UK.
Most important, the system seems to have worked. Guernsey regulators have
simply refused entry to all but what they believe are the most reputable
companies after careful vetting. That, officials say, provides a far tighter
net than exists on mainland UK. Barnett Christie, a small bank with
imprudent lending, is the only significant financial embarrassment to have
affected the island in recent years.
The questions for the regulators are whether they can continue to handle the
potential tensions of acting as both regulators and promoters of financial
services; and whether their fragile discretionary authority would hold up if
challenged in the courts.
A final issue is that of secrecy. Guernsey has 14,000 limited companies  -
more than 10 times the number per capita in the UK. Yet the only public
information available on each is a list of directors and shareholders. It is
impossible to find the annual accounts of any of these businesses, or the
identity of their beneficial owners.
</TEXT>
