<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Survey of Guernsey (2): Harsher climate for financial
services - In the past 20 years Guernsey has experienced dramatic change to
its economic base / The economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GUERNSEY has made its living in various ways over the centuries. In the
early 1800s, privateering flourished on the back of the Napoleonic wars.
Some of the proceeds from this lucrative trade were used to build up St
Peter Port, so that parts of the island's main town have a Georgian look to
this day.
In the late 1800s, there was brisk trade in dessert grapes. By the 1960s,
the main economic activity was the export of tomatoes and flowers. Tourism
was growing in importance.
But over the past 20 years Guernsey has experienced a dramatic change to its
economic base. On the one hand, horticulture has contracted because of
rising costs and falling prices, to a level where it represents 6 per cent
of gross national product today compared to 36 per cent in 1973.
On the other hand, financial services have grown to represent 51 per cent of
GNP in 1991, compared to 11 per cent in 1973. This arm of the economy is
further enhanced by another 20 per cent from the 'rentier' sector which
covers people whose main income is derived from investments such as deposit
interest, dividends, property and trusts.
The tourist sector has declined from 30 per cent of GNP in 1973 to 18 per
cent in 1991. There is a also a small industrial sector contributing 6 per
cent of GNP.
Some 16 per cent of the employed population now works in the financial
services industry with more than 300 employers. Approximately Pounds 32m in
income tax contributions were paid by the sector in 1990 - or 43 per cent of
the total.
There has been 15.6 per cent growth in population since the early 1970s and
gross national product at 1991 reflated prices has nearly doubled from
Pounds 434m in 1973 to Pounds 840m in 1991. Financial services have also
helped give Guernsey a self-supporting economy. Contrary to popular
supposition, it receives no grants from the mainland. It has no external
debt and it balances its budget each year.
The budget figures for 1993 show that of total current income of Pounds 154m
 -some 73 per cent of which is derived from income tax - Pounds 6.1m will be
put aside for capital expenditure.
The downside, if that is not too strong a word, of the growth is that by the
late 1980s the economy showed signs of overheating. By 1988 there was nil
unemployment. Foreign workers from Madeira were imported to work in
horticulture and tourism as locals were drawn off into financial services.
As local people started to receive good pay packets inflation crept up. It
was 8 per cent in 1990 while it was only 5.6 per cent on the mainland.
The pressures began to show up in housing. Although Guernsey has a two-tier
housing system with houses set aside for locals, prices rose sharply and
made it difficult for young people in particular to buy their own homes.
In order to try to balance the economy a little, the States tried, through
its budget, to subsidise horticulture for employment purposes. It arranged
cheap loans and in some cases gave grants. Mr John Dickson, head of
economics and statistics for the States, says: 'It was felt that we should
try and draw off some the wealth being made in financial services and make
sure that the rural economy survived.'
But recession, especially in tourism, has seen the Guernsey economy come
back in the past three years. Unemployment at 4 per cent is higher than it
has been for 15 years and inflation, at 3.5 per cent, is roughly in line
with that of Britain. There was little growth in the economy in 1991 and
little is expected for 1992.
For the future any attempt to encourage horticulture and industry will be
quietly dropped, according to Mr Dickson, and market forces will be allowed
to take their course. The emphasis will be on financial services, and trying
to revive tourism.
The going has got tougher. Mr John Roper, director-general of the Financial
Services Commission, says: 'The climate is harder for financial services if
for no other reason than interest rates in the UK, where much of the money
is deposited, have dropped substantially.' He believes, however, that
Guernsey is competitive and will continue to grow.
Tourism has failed to pick up because of recession. The tourism 'spend' is
put at Pounds 90m in 1992 compared with Pounds 120m in 1990.
Mr Mike Brown, head of the country's civil service, says: 'We are
optimistic. Financial services are not just one industry but many different
ones. There are all kinds of new products we can involve ourselves in. I am
sure the economy will pick up soon.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
