<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Consumer confidence drop
restrains Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
LEADING US stock prices moved in a narrow trading range yesterday after
sentiment was undermined by the news of a large fall in a closely watched
index of consumer confidence, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was up 2.17 at 3,457.27. The
more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 finished 1.20 firmer at 451.97,
while the American SE composite was a marginal 0.37 ahead at 419.68. Demand
for technology stocks was the driving force for an advance of 5.49 to 686.25
by the Nasdaq composite index.
New York SE trading volume totalled 230m shares, while rises held an
advantage over declines by 1,031 to 866.
There was no follow-through from Monday's solid gains, a reflection of
continued uncertainty about the outlook for the US economy. That mood of
uncertainty deepened after the Conference Board announced a decline in its
March consumer confidence index from 68.5 per cent to 62.6 per cent.
Analysts had been expecting the index to fall only slightly, and the news
upset the market, which has been concerned at the recent fragility of
consumer confidence in spite of the apparent strength of the economic
recovery.
Sentiment was also undermined by a drop in bond prices, which pushed the
yield on the benchmark 30-year government bond back up through 6.9 per cent.
Until last week, investors had hoped that bond yields would fall as low as
6.5 per cent, but since then the reversal in the bond market has dashed
those hopes.
Computer and technology issues were mixed. IBM, which had gained some ground
in recent days on the appointment of a new chairman, weakened Dollars 1 5/8
to Dollars 50 in volume of more than 2.5m shares, and Digital Equipment
dropped Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 43 7/8 . Some traders speculated that
renewed worries about another dividend cut from IBM were behind the selling.
In contrast elsewhere in the sector, Hewlett-Packard firmed Dollars 1 3/4 to
Dollars 75 3/4 and Compaq added Dollars 1 5/8 at Dollars 50 1/4 .
Wal-Mart tumbled Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars 31 1/8 in volume of 7m shares
after Prudential Securities, the Wall Street brokerage house, lowered its
forecast for the retailer's first-quarter net income from 21 cents a share
to 19 cents. Fisher-Price plunged Dollars 3 3/8 to Dollars 20 1/8 in volume
of 1.7m shares after the toy manufacturer announced late on Monday that it
expects its first-quarter revenues to be about 15 per cent lower than last
year's Dollars 146.8m.
Instrument Systems rose Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 6 7/8 following a ratings
upgrade from broking house Oppenheimer.
Among drug stocks, Marion Merrell Dow added Dollars 1 1/2 at Dollars 19 1/4
, Merck rose Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 35 7/8 , Johnson &amp; Johnson put on
Dollars 2 at Dollars 42 and Pfizer advanced Dollars 2 1/2 to Dollars 62 1/2
.
On the Nasdaq market, Commonwealth Bancshares soared Dollars 9 1/2 to
Dollars 42 3/4 on news that the company had signed a definitive pact to
merge with Meridian Bancorp in a Dollars 357m deal. Meridian eased Dollars
1/2 to Dollars 32 1/4 . Technology stocks were in demand, with Microsoft
climbing Dollars 4 to Dollars 91 in volume of 4.4m shares and Apple
appreciating Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 52 1/4 .
Canada
TORONTO ended slightly higher after brisk dealings as a surge in gold shares
offset losses in most other sectors. The Toronto SE said today's volume was
the sixth highest daily total on record.
The TSE 300 index gained a mere 0.9 at 3,586.1 and rises narrowly led falls
by 346 to 339 after volume of 66.9m shares.
The gold bullion price, which rallied to finish Cdollars 4.90 an ounce
higher, lifted Canadian gold shares.
