<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / International Company News: McIlwraith attracts ADollars
82.3m bid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MCILWRAITH McEacharn, the Australian transport and resources group,
yesterday welcomed a ADollars 1.95-per-share takeover offer from Cyprus
Australia Coal, a subsidiary of Cyprus Minerals of the US.
Mr Tony Lawrence, chairman, advised shareholders to take no immediate
action, but said Cyprus would be 'a suitable parent company for McIlwraith'.
The bid values the group at ADollars 82.3m (USDollars 59.2m).
Cyprus said its aim was to secure control of McIlwraith's 40 per cent stake
in Oakbridge, a New South Wales coal producer co-owned by Tomen Corporation
and Nippon Oil of Japan.
An agreement between the shareholders gives McIlwraith a majority on the
board of Oakbridge and the right to appoint the chairman. Oakbridge, which
has a market capitalisation of about ADollars 220m, made a net profit of
ADollars 5m last year.
Analysts said the bid was likely to prove attractive to TNT, the troubled
Australian transport group which owns 46 per cent of McIlwraith. TNT has
been seeking a buyer for its McIlwraith stake.
The offer is pitched at a premium of 25 per cent to McIlwraith's pre-bid
share price of ADollars 1.55. However, the shares were trading at ADollars
1.40 before bid speculation pushed up the price on Monday.
The bid depends on 90 per cent acceptance by shareholders and approval by
the Foreign Investment Review Board, which vets most takeover offers
involving overseas companies.
Other conditions require the Oakbridge share agreement to remain unchanged,
and the retention by Oakbridge of all assets valued at more than ADollars
2m.
</TEXT>
