<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / International Company News: Delta pilots' union seeks
justification for lay-offs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UNION representing pilots at Delta Air Lines, one of the big three US
carriers, said yesterday it wanted to 'validate' the need to lay off 600
pilots as result of the airline's 'fleet simplification' plan. Delta
announced the furloughs - its first temporary lay-offs of permanent staff
for 36 years - on Monday.
'We think the numbers are on the high side,' said the Air Line Pilots'
Association. But Alpa added that, if the lay-offs were shown to be justified
on economic grounds, it would be willing to resume talks with management
over a wage concession package.
When the airline announced the planned furloughs, Mr Ron Allen, Delta
chairman, stressed that they should be seen as part of a 'fleet
simplification' plan. But the move was interpreted as a shot across the bows
of the pilots' union. Pilots are the only unionised labour group at Delta
and the one group which has so far failed to agree a package of wage cuts.
The fleet simplification plan, Delta said, would involve the retirement of
some Airbus A310 aircraft, which the company took over from the now-defunct
Pan Am in 1991, and of some Boeing 727s.
Delta said these moves rendered 600 pilots surplus, including a number of
former Pan Am pilots.
</TEXT>
