<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / International Company News: Apple, Honeywell in cockpit deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
APPLE Macintosh personal computers will find their way into the cockpits of
commercial aircraft as a result of an agreement reached between Apple and
Honeywell's Commercial Flight Systems Group.
Under the deal, Honeywell will develop an 'electronic library' for use by
flight crews, providing 'multi-media' versions of maintenance and operation
manuals that incorporate video, graphics and sound as well as text.
Honeywell will also make a 'ruggedised' version of Apple's
recently-introduced Macintosh Quadra 800 high-performance PC for the cockpit
information system.
The agreement marks the first time that Apple has licensed its Macintosh
computer technology under such an Original Equipment Manufacturer agreement
and signals a new strategy by Apple to broaden the markets for its
technology.
Honeywell said it plans to provide its airline customers with an easy-to-use
information system. The cockpit Macintosh computers will also be able to run
standard PC software.
'This provides airborne software application compatibility with computer
systems on the ground, and should help to incorporate more fully the
aircraft into an airline's overall information management system,' said Mr
Mark Anderson, Honeywell's lead engineer for the ELS project.
The agreement with Honeywell is the first to be reached by a new group
formed at Apple. Called 'New Media/New Markets,' the group will focus on
opportunities created by the convergence of the publishing, entertainment,
telecommunications, computing and consumer electronics businesses, Apple
said.
'Apple believes Macintosh personal computing technology can add great value
outside the realm of the traditional personal computer market,' said Mr Fred
Forsyth, senior vice-president and general manager of the Macintosh Systems
Division.' In particular, Apple is targeting areas such as retail,
automotive, transportation, medical imaging and aviation.
</TEXT>
