FT  31 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Delay for Mosaic relisting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOSAIC Investments, the West Midlands-based mini-conglomerate whose shares
have been suspended since last September, yesterday announced interim
results for the period to October 31 1992 and said it hoped to get its
shares relisted by the end of April.
Mosaic had previously said its shares should be relisted by today.
However, the complexity of discussions with bankers, Mr Rodney Day, the
holder of Pounds 3m worth of preference shares, and other vendors of
companies bought by Mosaic, have delayed the process. Worsening trading
conditions meant earlier agreements had to be renegotiated.
The interim results showed a pre-tax profit of Pounds 207,000 (Pounds 3.2m).
The sale of the engineering and automotive division cut sales by Pounds 4.2m
and operating profits by Pounds 900,000 but boosted net assets from Pounds
7.3m to Pounds 10.5m.
Group sales fell from Pounds 25.8m to Pounds 18.3m, and operating profits
were Pounds 1.4m (Pounds 3.8m).
Exceptional costs of Pounds 583,000 related to redundancy and reorganisation
costs and more costs are expected in the second half because of the
relisting.
There was a Pounds 349,000 loss (loss Pounds 28,000) from the investment in
European Licensing Group, the associate.
The loss on the sale of the engineering and automotive business caused an
extraordinary debit of Pounds 2.8m.
Losses per share were 0.67p (earnings 12.8p).
