<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Daimler-Benz to list in Singapore and Shanghai after US
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON, DAVID WALLER, TONY WALKER and CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, FRANKFURT, PEKING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DAIMLER-BENZ intends next year to seek a stock-exchange listing of its
shares in Singapore, and possibly Shanghai, after reaching agreement with US
authorities about a listing in New York.
The plans for the listings were revealed in New York yesterday at a press
conference to announce Daimler's compromise with the US Securities and
Exchange Commission.
Mr Gerhard Liener, the group's finance director, said that the agreement on
accounting standards with the US authorities would lead directly to listings
of its stock on other exchanges worldwide. Daimler shares are already traded
in Tokyo.
Mr Liener said yesterday that the listing in New York would not be coupled
with the issue of new stock. Daimler's long-awaited rights issue would come
'probably next year', he said.
Daimler had intended to hold a DM2bn (Pounds 800m) rights issue in the
autumn of last year but this was postponed due to the poor state of the
stock market.
Mr Liener said yesterday that Daimler's net profit for 1991 would be 'just
under' DM1.5bn after DM1.9bn in 1991. This is in line with analysts'
expectations and reflects a sharp downturn in the group's core automobile
market. Full details are to be released next week.
Mr Liener said that turnover for 1992 would be DM98.5bn, up from DM95.01 in
1991. The dividend is to be maintained at 1991's DM13 per share.
The deal with the SEC means that Daimler's group accounts will in future be
produced accounting to US generally accepted accounting practice (GAAP).
This will mean common standards of valuation applied throughout the group,
and greater disclosure in areas such as cash flow statements.
Preparations for the listing in Shanghai's fledgling markets are at an early
stage but the intention underscores German industry's growing interest in
China.
Daimler is considering opening a bus assembly factory near Shanghai and
setting up a joint venture with a local company to make rolling stock for
underground railways. AEG, Daimler's electrical's subsidiary, is leader of a
German consortium which has built the first 14km of an underground railway
for Shanghai.
If Daimler joins the Shanghai stock exchange it will be sharing the register
with companies such as No. 1 Pencil, Fridge Compressor and Rubber Belt, Tony
Walker writes from Peking.
The exchange has a reputation as a roller coaster. In mid-1992 the B-share
index, the exchange's 10 dollar-denominated shares available to foreigners,
dropped 50 per cent before recovering some ground. Last week, it dropped 5
per cent, before rebounding.
Blazing a trail, page 28
Another two senior executives have quit Volkswagen, the German car group
which is Europe's leading vehicle maker, writes Christopher Parkes in
Frankfurt.
Mr Hans-Jorg Hungerland, a director in charge of world distribution of VW
brand vehicles, and Mr William Young, president of Volkswagen of America,
both left at their own request, the company said yesterday.
The moves follow the departure of three group main board directors and the
arrival of General Motors' former head of procurement, Mr Jose Ignacio Lopez
de Arriortua.
</TEXT>
