<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Lord Hollick and Paul Foot leave the Daily Mirror
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE uncertainty over the future of Mirror Group Newspapers intensified
yesterday with the resignation of two very different men - Lord Hollick, a
non-executive director, and Mr Paul Foot, long-standing Daily Mirror
columnist.
Both personified the traditional links between Mirror Group Newspapers and
support for the Labour Party.
Last month Lord Hollick, the Labour peer and chief executive of MAI, the
financial services and television company, found himself in a minority of
one on the MGN board.
Lord Hollick said then that he could not support fully the view of his
fellow directors. The board had backed the policy of Mr David Montgomery,
the chief executive.
Yesterday he said in a statement: 'I have for several months voiced my
concerns about a number of governance and policy matters which I believe to
be important to the long-term commercial and editorial success of Mirror
Group Newspapers.'
He added: 'Unfortunately it has not been possible to resolve these matters
and I have therefore tendered my resignation. I wish MGN every success.'
Lord Hollick was not immediately available for any further comment but it is
believed he was concerned about the editorial independence of the paper, the
strength of its commitment to Labour, the number of journalists hired from
Today - which Mr Montgomery used to edit - and the way Mirror staff have
been treated.
He is also concerned about the effect that a weakening of the paper's
traditional links with Labour could have on its business prospects. The
Mirror's political stance has usually been seen as an important part of its
appeal to readers.
Mr Foot, the award-winning journalist who last week tried unsuccessfully to
publish a column critical of Daily Mirror management, said in a letter to Mr
David Banks, the Daily Mirror editor, that his position had become
impossible.
After Mr Foot handed out copies of his unpublished page in the street
outside the Daily Mirror building last week Mr Banks issued a statement
saying Mr Foot should take sick leave to rest.
The Mirror editor said yesterday Mr Foot had done the honourable thing and
that he would be replaced this week.
Sir Robert Clark, the MGN chairman said last night that it was not
surprising that Lord Hollick had decided to resign since he was unable to
support the position of the board.
'Good corporate governance was observed to the highest standards and in all
respects at Mirror Group,' Sir Robert said.
