<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Analyst fined over insider deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Thorold Mackie, a Scottish investment analyst, was yesterday found guilty
of insider dealing at the Court of Session in Edinburgh. He was fined Pounds
25,000.
The verdict, by a majority of the 15-member jury in Scotland's principal
court, shocked people in the Edinburgh financial community, where Mr Mackie
is a well-known figure.
The trial, which lasted seven days, concerned a profits warning by the
Glasgow-based waste disposal company Shanks &amp; McEwan. Mr Peter Runciman,
chairman of SME, had told the court that in September 1991 he informed Mr
Mackie in confidence that SME was shortly to issue a profits warning.
Mr Mackie was accused under the 1985 Company Securities (Insider Dealing)
Act of 'counselling and procuring' two salesmen at Bell Lawrie White, the
Edinburgh stockbrokers for which he worked, to deal in SME shares on behalf
of clients.
By selling ahead of the profits warning the shares realised Pounds 1.396m
more than they would have done after the warning was issued, the court
heard.
Mr Mackie had told the court that Mr Runciman did not mention a profits
warning at the meeting, but told him that there would be 'little by way of
growth in earnings per share' for SME in the current half year.
Temporary judge Sheriff Robin McEwan, QC, told Mr Mackie, 39, that 'insider
dealing was a modern creation which nevertheless has to be regarded
seriously. The probity of dealing on a public stock exchange and the
confidence of the public are of great importance in this country.'
He acknowledged that Mr Mackie's offence had not been committed for personal
gain, but as a consequence of it Bell Lawrie White had transacted business
for which it must have earned considerable fees.
In mitigation Mr Donald Macfadyen, QC, defending, said that Mr Mackie had
been suspended from membership of the Securities and Futures Authority when
he was charged a year ago.
This had prevented him from advising clients in a professional capacity, and
his membership was now likely to be terminated, he said.
Mr Mackie is understood to be considering an appeal.
Anxiety over trial, Page 10
</TEXT>
