<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Observer: Object lesson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
For all Jacques Attali's vocal support for the Russians' reform programme,
the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development's chairman gave signs
of thinking they had gone a bit far yesterday in demonstrating their need
for western aid.
His visit to the country's provinces was cut short by a truck which ripped
into his bullet-proof limousine. Although the crash was spectacular, the
50-year-old escaped with scratches to his face. But when his apologetic
hosts blamed the accident on primitive Russian highways, he replied:
'In Stalin's time, you would no doubt have been sent to the camps for an
accident involving a foreign guest. Today, all you are doing is asking an
international institution for money to improve your roads.'
Fortunately, by the time he dined with local officials and industrial
managers in the historic town of Suzdal, he'd relented enough to promise he
would return.
