<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
It is right that television should be doing whatever it can to ease the
problems of the homeless, though experience over some decades should have
taught us by now that, with homelessness as with violence, television has
precious little effect. As part of its 'Gimme Shelter' season, Channel 4
repeats the famous 1966 BBC drama Cathy Come Home (10.35). In its time this
was thought to be tremendously influential; it was regarded as a truism that
it led directly to the formation of the charity Shelter, even though Des
Wilson, who ran Shelter, denies it. And today there are more homeless in
Britain than when the drama was first shown. Better, however, to see it and
have your heartstrings tugged than not to see it. In Bookmark Simon Armitage
goes in search of fellow poet Weldon Kees who, in 1955, abandoned his car on
the Golden Gate Bridge and disappeared (8.10 BBC2). The same channel screens
the second episode of Goggle Eyes (9.25) the story of a new man in the life
of a one-parent family, with splendid performances from Honeysuckle Weeks
and Victoria Shalet as sisters.
</TEXT>
<XX>
