<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Smith senses schism over future
voting plan - Labour is still warring over PR as the Plant committee
concludes its inquiry today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TO THE senior Labour party official, the dilemma was simple: 'How can you be
a party of change and not change on PR?
If you do opt for change, how do you counter the Tory argument that you
don't believe you can win an election by the present system?'
If he were not so before, Mr John Smith, Labour's leader, must now be aware
that the potentially explosive electoral reform issue could split his party
as damagingly as Maastricht has divided the Tories.
Today, as Lord Plant's exhaustive three-year trawl through the issues
involved comes to its formal end, the fierce disagreements within his
18-member working party are about the only element in the equation not in
dispute.
Another might be that the only game in town is what happens to the House of
Commons. Even opponents of any change from first-past-the-post for MPs, like
Mrs Margaret Beckett, the deputy leader, can probably live with alternatives
for Europe, local government, Scotland and the Lords. But when it comes to
the lower chamber, schism is in the air.
Lord Plant, a politics professor from Southampton University, has always
said that his warring colleagues must table a report with recommendations.
But with committee members split three ways between three systems, it
appears clear there is no outright majority for any one.
So how is a conclusion reached? Lord Plant - now regarded as firmly in the
reformist camp - is expected to insist that members first vote for or
against change. Some, Mrs Beckett once again is one, may strenuously object
as such a vote would almost certainly produce a majority for change. But
what change? Neither of the two hybrid systems on offer - Supplementary Vote
and the Mixed Member System - can command a majority of the committee.
One insider said: 'The first hour and half of the meeting will probably be
spent arguing how the vote on the committee is going to be taken.'
The protests of advocates of first-past-the-post must also be accommodated,
probably requiring a further 'final' drafting meeting before the finished
report is sent on to the National Executive Committee's meeting at the end
of April.
Party officials have hinted that Mr Smith, a known sceptic about change,
must make his own views known by then. He may do so only privately. As the
ultimate decisions still lie with party conference, the key battles now lie,
as so often, within the executive committees of the big unions.
Mr Bill Morris, the Transport Union's general secretary, surprised many last
year when he came out for reform. His executive, however, is not yet with
certainty in the reformers' bag. Similar hints of flexibility have come from
the highly influential GMB general union which is said to have pledged to do
what Mr Smith wants.
So what does Mr Smith want? The simple answer is to win the next election.
Even if that can only be achieved by having Mr Paddy Ashdown as his deputy,
Mr Smith might swallow hard and bear it - though never publicly in a pact.
But he is said to be unconvinced that Labour has a better chance as an
electoral reforming party than not.
If Mr Smith comes out firmly against change, he can be sure the reformers'
campaign will continue.
One final option, mooted recently, is to promise a referendum on the issue,
along the lines of the recent plebiscite in New Zealand. But that might
prove awkward at a time when Labour is so adamantly opposed to a referendum
on Maastricht.
Mr Smith might just be tempted to do what Labour leaders are traditionally
least naturally disposed to do - let the conference decide, then try and
make the decision stick.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>MGMT  Management.
    CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
