   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EMPLOYMENT bill faces what could be a record number of 300 amendments as
it goes through its committee stage in the House of Lords, David Goodhart
writes.
The bill, which is due to become law before parliament's summer recess, has
already been the subject of dozens of mainly technical amendments at
committee and report stages in the Commons.
Although most amendments have been tabled by opposition members and peers,
Conservative members have also been giving voice to the anxieties of
employers' organisations about the burdens that some measures are imposing.
In the latest significant amendment, inspired by the Confederation of
British Industry, women going on maternity leave will be required to inform
their employer when they are leaving and when they plan to return.
