<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Finance community in shock: James Buxton reports on the
conviction of a Scottish analyst for insider dealing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE conviction yesterday of Mr Thorold Mackie for insider dealing was
greeted with shock by many in the Edinburgh financial community last night.
'It's a travesty, it's appalling,' said a bank official who knows him well
and had followed the trial closely.
Mr Mackie, 39, is probably the best-known investment analyst in Scotland and
his fate aroused personal sympathy. It also caused anxiety  - the offence of
which he was found guilty concerned information given by a company chairman
to an investment analyst, routine business in the Edinburgh financial
community.
Although the trial was held at the Court of Session in Edinburgh under
Scottish judicial procedures, the offence was against UK-wide law - the 1985
Companies Securities (Insider Dealing) Act. It was the first case of its
kind in Scotland but the offence could equally have been committed in
England.
The crux of the case against Mr Mackie was that in September 1991 he had
been informed by Mr Peter Runciman, then chairman of the waste disposal
company Shanks &amp; McEwan, that the company was about to issue a profits
warning - a piece of acutely price-sensitive information.
Mr Mackie, it was alleged, then 'counselled and procured' two salesmen in
Bell Lawrie White, the stockbrokers for which he worked, to deal in the
shares. By selling clients' shares ahead of the profits warning the shares
realised Pounds 1.39m more than if they had been sold after the warning.
The trial therefore concerned the passing-on of a specific piece of
price-sensitive information, rather than the more general information a
company might routinely give to an analyst and which might lead to share
dealing.
Mr Mackie said Mr Runciman did not mention a profits warning at their
meeting, only telling him that Shanks &amp; McEwan would enjoy 'little by way of
growth in earnings per share' in that half year, as part of a general
briefing.
As with so many things in Scotland, the trial involved people who know each
other very well. Mr Runciman and Mr Mackie were on first-name terms; both
have fairly high profiles and are respected in the Scottish business and
financial communities. Bell Lawrie White is the leading stockbroker in
Edinburgh.
During the seven-day trial, a series of stockbrokers, analysts and fund
managers from Edinburgh and London - the court heard 21 witnesses in all -
gave evidence against Mr Mackie. Other members of the Edinburgh financial
community dropped in on the Court of Session, the principal court in
Scotland, just off the Royal Mile in the heart of the city, to hear what was
going on.
Few of them, it seems, expected Mr Mackie to be found guilty. The majority
verdict appeared to take even Mr Mackie's legal team by surprise.
Mr Mackie made his name in the tightly knit Scottish financial community -
which concentrates on life assurance, fund management and banking - for
specialising in Scottish quoted companies, of which there are about 60. He
frequently complained that Scotland was producing so few of them.
Until he dropped out of the limelight after being charged with insider
dealing a year ago, he was frequently quoted in the Scottish press and on
the radio.
In court he looked a rather lonely figure, sitting upright on a long bench,
alone except for a policeman at a respectful distance. Flashes of his dry
sense of humour emerged when he went into the witness box on Monday.
Mr Runciman, 64, is an Englishman who was recruited in the early 1980s as a
company doctor to Shanks &amp; McEwan, then a privately owned and ailing Glasgow
company. Through a spectacular purchase of landfill sites from Hanson in
1986 he built the company into one of Britain's biggest waste-disposal
operators and became a very wealthy man after it was listed on the Stock
Exchange in 1988.
A courteous, almost diffident man, he gave evidence in a quiet but
determined way. He retired from Shanks &amp; McEwan at the end of last year, and
is treasurer of the Scottish Conservative party.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
