FT  31 MAR 93 / Boost in business property market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE IN the commercial property market has risen markedly, according
to a survey of property lenders.
Nearly three quarters of the 69 banks and financial institutions questioned
by Chesterton Financial, the chartered surveyor, expect an improvement in
the market during the next year. Last July, by contrast, fewer than half the
bankers polled expected a recovery over the following 12 months.
The recovery is thought unlikely to take hold until the autumn. Only 22 per
cent of respondents see an improvement in the next six months.
Lenders were more optimistic about an improvement in the market than at any
time since the survey was started in July 1991. But most property lenders
report growing problems with bad debts. A majority expect the number of
receiverships to rise over the next six months.
The Association of Risk Managers in Industry and Commerce yesterday
criticised the Association of British Insurers and the Department of Trade
and Industry for their response to providing cover for terrorist damage.
Ms Liz Taylor, who chairs the risk managers, said Pool Re, the terrorist
damage insurance pool, had been devised without consultation with clients or
brokers. 'Pool Re has been hastily conceived with considerable government
strictures,' she said, adding that the managing director had few resources
to assist his work.
But she called for support of Pool Re and warned that it might otherwise
founder.
Chesterton Financial/CSW Confidence Barometer. Chesterton Financial
Services, 54 Brook St, London W1. Free
