<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / London Transport warns on spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON'S BUSES as well as its Underground will suffer under government
spending cuts in the coming financial year, London Transport warned in its
annual business plan published yesterday.
The plan says London Transport's programme of improvements has had to be
sharply cut because of a 30 per cent reduction in government grant from
Pounds 768m in 1992-93 to Pounds 540m in 1993-94.
Sir Wilfrid Newton, London Transport's chairman, says in the report: 'Having
raised the expectations of passengers, suppliers and staff, London Transport
is now faced with the prospect of cutting back programmes, winding down
project teams and releasing skilled resources.'
One casualty will be an extension to the dot-matrix passenger information
system at bus stops, introduced last November on one route. The system will
now be delayed.
The biggest project still going ahead this year will be the upgrading of the
Central Line, which involves the introduction of new trains and a
resignalling of much of the route. But similar work on the Northern Line has
been postponed.
The planned extension of the Jubilee Line to Docklands remains uncertain
because a funding scheme has still not been agreed with the private sector.
Annual Business Plan 1993-94. London Transport, 55 Broadway, London SW1H
0BD. Free.
</TEXT>
