FT  31 MAR 93 / Call for day off to beat rail strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS and CHRISTIAN BOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES should work out which jobs employees could do from home on Friday
or give them the day off because of the threatened national rail strike, the
Institute of Management said yesterday .
Staying at home 'would be better than sitting in a traffic jam for three
hours, arriving at the office in a stinking mood and then having to leave
after a couple of hours', the institute said.
Not everyone could work from home, the institute said, 'but you can do a
fair amount of work or catch up on reading and correspondence'.
The one-day strike by members of the Rail, Maritime and Transport union is
over threatened compulsory British Rail redundancies and the use of outside
contractors.
In a separate dispute, many London buses will also be off the road on
Friday. Bus staff are protesting, in their third day of action, over wage
cuts and longer working hours.
The rail and the bus strikes coincide with a one-day strike by the National
Union of Mineworkers over pit closures.
The Institute of Management's advice to employers to draw up contingency
plans appeared yesterday to be largely unnecessary, and there was little
enthusiasm for the idea of a day's holiday for staff, or working from home.
The banks did not expect to have to close any branches: Midland, for
example, will provide coaches for its staff. Legal &amp; General is also laying
on coaches, and groups of employees are arranging to share cars.
Workers at local BT centres could find themselves distracted from their
duties by extra bodies - staff unable to reach their workplace are supposed
to report to their nearest office. BT admitted it was usually difficult to
find volunteers anything to do for the day.
</TEXT>
