FT  31 MAR 93 / Company fleet tax regime welcomed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW company car taxation rules to be introduced in April next year, based on
a percentage of car list prices, were welcomed as more fair than the present
system by two thirds of companies questioned at last week's Company Car
Business Show.
Even the Budget's 8 per cent increase in road tax charges - well in excess
of inflation - was regarded as 'realistic' by 41 per cent of the
respondents, undertaken by the car leasing subsidiary of BRS, the
fleet-management group.
The main criticism of the new system was its retention of the present system
of business mileage bands under which high business mileage drivers pay
substantially less tax on their company car benefit than drivers for whom
their car is mainly a perk.
More than three quarters of the 76 companies questioned said that would
encourage drivers to continue running up unnecessary business mileage to
achieve the lower tax thresholds.
Fifty nine per cent of companies said they felt the new system would lead to
more employees opting for a cash alternative to their company cars.
Management, Page 17
</TEXT>
