<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Sex bias ruling extends benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOMEN claiming severe disablement and invalid care allowances will be
entitled to receive benefits until they are 65 following a ruling by the
European Court of Justice yesterday.
The Luxembourg court ruled that the social security secretary was not
justified in denying women access to the benefits - which are linked to
state pension ages - because they are over 60.
Reliance on the discriminatory state pension ages to deny women access to
these benefits was in breach of the European directive on statutory social
security which requires that men and women be treated equally, the court
said.
The case, backed by the Equal Opportunities Commission, was brought by five
women who had been forced to give up work either through their own
ill-health or the need to care for severely disabled dependants.
They were prevented from claiming invalid care allowance and severe
disablement allowance because they were over 60 and the upper limit for
receiving those benefits is 60 for women and 65 for men, in line with state
pension ages.
The case meant that other women who would have lost benefits at 60 because
of the state pension age for women will receive such benefits for an
additional five years, the commission said. It added that 1,500 other cases
are waiting for rulings.
Mr Alan Lakin, the commission's chief legal adviser, said the case 'shows
yet again the extent of the sex discrimination and confusion which comes
from different state pension ages'.
He said the commission was looking forward to the government's white paper
on equalising state pension ages in the hope that some of these anomalies
could be sorted out.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
