<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Watchdog criticises councils' tendering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RHODRI DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL AUTHORITIES must review their compulsory competitive tendering
practices to make them more responsive to consumers, according to a report
published today.
The report by the Audit Commission - local government's watchdog - says some
services that are contracted out are breaking down or of a poor standard. In
a survey of 150 schools, a third expressed dissatisfaction with services
such as cleaning and catering supplied by contractors.
Poor contract conditions, lack of competition for contracts and authorities'
ignorance of consumer needs had contributed to a tendering initiative
'fraught with problems', says the report.
Since the 1988 Local Government Finance Act, Pounds 2bn of local authority
services, mostly refuse collection and school catering, have been subject to
tendering. The report says three-quarters of companies that expressed an
initial interest in contracts failed to bid. Almost 85 per cent of contracts
were awarded to councils' own direct services organisations.
In spite of an overall reduction of 7 per cent in the cost of contracted
services, the scarcity of private sector tenderers could be hindering
greater efficiency and value for money, according to the report.
Recommendations to attract private sector bids include regular meetings
between authorities and their present contractors, and more precise contract
framing. There should also be greater consultation between authorities and
schools and colleges before contracts are drafted. 'It's necessary to
consider the needs of consumers rather than the client department,' the
report says.
Realising the Benefits of Competition. Audit Commission. HMSO. Pounds 8.50.
</TEXT>
<XX>
