<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Mixed start to pollution permit sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US Environmental Protection Agency said yesterday it had taken in
Dollars 21.4m (Pounds 15m) from the landmark auction of air pollution
allowances, its market-based scheme to reduce acid rain.
However, most of the allowances offered by private companies failed to fetch
their minimum prices and were not sold. Allowances allocated to the auction
by the EPA had no minimum bid, and all found buyers. It received 171 bids.
The pollution emission permits are granted to 110 of the largest sulphur
dioxide (SO) polluters, all of them coal-burning electricity utilities, in
the first phases of the EPA's clean-air programme. Companies may trade
allowances that are surplus to their own needs.
Bids came from power companies, coal producers, environmentalists and
smokestack industries for the rights to emit 275,510 tons of SO into the air
after 1995. In the end only 150,010 tons of emission permits were sold. The
average price per tonne of SO emissions was Dollars 439 for permits up to
1999, the first phase of the two-phase programme, with the lowest successful
bid Dollars 122 and the highest Dollars 450.
Brokers bidding for industry took about 5 per cent of the total. A few
public interest groups, including environmentalists, made token purchases of
the allowance. Utilities, predictably, were the biggest buyers, with
Carolina Power and Light the largest.
The auction, finalised on Monday, was conducted by the Chicago Board of
Trade.
The fact that virtually no allowances offered by utilities were sold bodes
poorly for the CBOT's plans to sponsor a series of similar auctions starting
in June, as a precursor to its planned SO futures and options markets. All
of its allowances will be privately offered and presumably will have minimum
prices.
The prices reached at auction were substantially below the cost of
installing air-cleaning scrubbers or switching to low-sulphur fuel, and were
also below rates established in private transactions for the allowances.
Mr Richard Sandor, an architect of the CBOT's planned emissions futures
market, said price competition from the allowance programme had already
forced the costs of clean air compliance lower. The EPA said its economic
models demonstrated that the allowance programme had cut the cost of
emissions compliance in half for electricity utility rate payers.
Mr Andrew Weissman, of Clean Air Capital Markets, a Washington-based
investment banking firm, believes the auction format is inappropriate for
pricing the allowances, and fears the low prices will deliver the wrong
message to the market.
He said the sale's timing hurt prices. 'The nature of compliance planning is
you need a long lead time. The auction came too late for phase one
compliance plans, and was a little too early for companies planning for the
second phase of emission standards.'
Illinois Power, a mid-west electricity utility, recently elected to buy SO
allowances from other utilities and delay installing scrubbing technology.
It is hoping the delay will allow it to purchase more advanced technology
when scrubbers are finally installed in its smokestacks in 1999.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
