<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Juppe faces tussle over foreign policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN THEORY President Francois Mitterrand is free to object to any of the
suggested candidates for the French cabinet, in practice he needs a very
sound reason to do so, writes Alice Rawsthorn. He must have wished he could
have found such a reason to stop Mr Alain Juppe from becoming foreign
minister.
Mr Juppe, 47, is, after all, a close friend and political confidant of the
president's old adversary, Mr Jacques Chirac, mayor of Paris and leader of
the RPR. The new foreign minister was also one of the loudest voices calling
last week for the septuagenarian Socialist president to resign.
The president managed to quell the resignation calls by threatening not to
appoint a prime minister from any party - namely the RPR - which was calling
for his own dismissal. But the choice of Mr Juppe as foreign minister must
have irked him almost as much as having to accept Mr Francois Leotard at
defence, a post the president refused to give him in the last cohabitation
government.
Mr Mitterrand may yet get his revenge. The ambitious Mr Juppe, a graduate of
the elite Ecole National de l'Administration, has been overshadowed by Mr
Chirac ever since he joined the latter's private office in 1976. He was
lumbered with the low-profile job of budget minister in the last
cohabitation government and sees the Foreign Ministry as way to make his
mark on the political scene.
But foreign affairs is one of the key areas of policy that Mr Mitterrand is
determined to cling on to as head of state. The previous cohabitation
administration was marked by humiliating scenes as Mr Mitterrand upstaged Mr
Chirac, then premier, and his conservative ministers on the international
summit circuit.
Mr Mitterrand has already made it quite clear that he has no intention of
behaving any differently in the second round of cohabitation. Mr Juppe now
faces the tricky task of trying to wrest control of foreign policy from the
president, at the same time as he attempts to fulfil his own aims of
renegotiating the Gatt reforms and cementing the relationship between France
and Germany.
</TEXT>
