<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / Joint approach urged in policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE should set up a national security council in which its Socialist
president and its new conservative government could jointly run the
country's foreign and defence policy, an influential Gaullist adviser
suggested yesterday.
Mr Pierre Lelouche, foreign affairs adviser to Mr Jacques Chirac and now an
RPR deputy, wrote in Liberation newspaper yesterday that joint
decision-making in such a council could avoid possible paralysis of French
policy on issues such as defence, the European Community and the Gatt trade
talks, where President Mitterrand and the right had differences of view.
Mr Mitterrand has made it clear he will exercise the influence allowed him
by the constitution in foreign and defence policy. However cohabitation -
the term used to describe periods in which France is governed by a president
and prime minister of opposing parties - has got off to a smooth start. Mr
Mitterrand last night approved the cabinet nominees of the new premier, Mr
Edouard Balladur of the RPR, in record time.
Mr Jean-Louis Bianco, who was Mr Mitterrand's chief of staff at the Elysee
in the last cohabitation government of 1986-88, yesterday warned the new
government against the temptation to 'hide things' from the president.
A new computer network linking the Elysee to the Quai d'Orsay's diplomatic
cable traffic would make concealment harder now.
Interest rates in the French franc money market fell sharply yesterday amid
growing speculation that the Bank of France may cut the country's official
interest rates this week, writes James Blitz.
One-month French franc interest rates fell more than a full percentage point
from 11.20 per cent to 10.18 per cent. Three-month interest rates fell from
11.00 per cent to below 10 per cent.
