<HEADLINE>
FT  31 MAR 93 / French right in proposal to help 'cohabitation'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE should set up a national security council in which its Socialist
president and its new conservative government could jointly run the
country's foreign and defence policy, an influential Gaullist adviser
suggested yesterday.
Mr Pierre Lelouche, foreign affairs adviser to Mr Jacques Chirac and now an
RPR deputy, wrote in the Liberation newspaper yesterday that joint
decision-making in such a council could avoid possible paralysis of French
policy on issues such as defence, the European Community and the Gatt trade
talks, where President Mitterrand and the right had genuine differences of
view.
The new era of cohabitation - the term used to describe periods in which
France is governed by a president and prime minister of opposing parties -
got off to a smooth start. Mr Mitterrand rapidly named Mr Edouard Balladur
of the RPR as the new prime minister within a day of the centre-right's
sweeping parliamentary victory on Sunday, and promised to 'respect
scrupulously' the new majority's general policy.
But there is still the possibility of early conflict over the composition of
Mr Balladur's cabinet, announced last night. Mr Mitterrand may yet baulk at
Mr Balladur's nominations for foreign and defence minister, areas of policy
in which the president made clear on Monday night he would exercise the
influence which the constitution gives him.
Mr Jean-Louis Bianco, who was Mr Mitterrand's chief of staff at the Elysee
in the last cohabitation government of 1986-88, yesterday warned the new
government against the temptation to 'hide things' from the president.
A new computer network linking the Elysee to the Quai d'Orsay's diplomatic
cable traffic would make concealment harder now.
Meanwhile, the manoeuvring between the RPR and UDF components of the new
ruling coalition intensified yesterday over not only ministerial posts but
also that of president of the National Assembly. In return for early
endorsement of Mr Balladur as prime minister, Mr Valery Giscard d'Estaing,
the UDF leader, said his party should get the top parliamentary post,
perhaps - some suspect - for himself because, like Mr Chirac, he is staying
out of the government.
</TEXT>
