<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / Heseltine tells Commons his plan offers coal's 'best hope'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HESELTINE last night used the promise of 'hundreds of millions of
pounds' in subsidies to the coal industry in a bid to snuff out a possible
Conservative backbench revolt over last week's government white paper.
There was 'a significant new market to go for', the trade and industry
secretary said, as he defended his white paper in front of a sceptical
Commons. 'We have made it clear that the best hope for British Coal is to
take advantage of the opportunity we have provided.'
But a series of interventions by possible Tory rebels indicated that Mr
Heseltine had not completely calmed fears that the 12 reprieved pits might
not survive for more than a year.
These were played on by Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary,
in a spirited plea to Tory MPs to join Labour in voting down the white
paper.
Today was the day for Tories who had voiced displeasure at the original pit
closure announcement last October to make good the promises they had made
five months ago to Britain's mining communities, Mr Cook argued.
The exchanges came as the coal and electricity industries completed the
signing of contracts for the sale of 160m tonnes of coal over five years,
leaving the way clear for talks to begin on extra sales aimed at saving the
12 reprieved pits.
Among Tory backbenchers who intervened in Mr Heseltine's speech, Mr Nicholas
Winterton, the MP for Macclesfield, asked why he was not acting to engineer
a level playing field for coal in competition with other fuels.
Mr Winston Churchill, leader of the Tory backbench coal group, charged
British Coal with 'directly sabotaging' Mr Heseltine's statement to MPs last
week.
British Coal yesterday joined Mr Heseltine in admitting it could not
forecast how big the extra market above the core contract would be. 'The
generators and rest of electricity industry will effectively decide the
future for our pits,' the company said. Prospects would also depend on the
terms of a subsidy to help marginal pits compete.
Mr Heseltine riled opposition MPs by dwelling at length on Labour policy on
coal in the 1970s. This prompted the retort from Mr Cook that the trade and
industry secretary should have spared MPs his 'rendition of a pantomime
villain'.
Politics and Parliament, Page 15
</TEXT>
