<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / International Company News: Lehman Bros co-president quits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON and MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR TOMILSON Hill resigned yesterday as co-president of Lehman Brothers, the
Wall Street investment bank, after Mr Richard Fuld was appointed sole
president of the firm by Mr Harvey Golub, chairman of American Express,
Lehman's parent group
The departure of Mr Hill from Lehman was unexpected. He had run the
investment banking and trading operation in tandem with Mr Fuld since 1990.
Both were veterans of the firm, which was part of the Shearson Lehman
integrated securities house until earlier this month when the Shearson
brokerage unit was sold to Primerica. Before the sale, Mr Hill had been
co-chief operating officer of Shearson Lehman with Mr Fuld.
Mr Harvey Golub, in a letter to Lehman staff, said yesterday that he had
decided that a single leader of Lehman's management would 'reduce the
potential for confusion about responsibility and authority' within the firm.
The ascension of Mr Fuld, a former bond trader, to the pole position at
Lehman represents another victory for bond traders on Wall Street. In recent
years, the huge profits generated by fixed income sales and trading have
lifted bond specialists to the tops of their firms, while colleagues from
more traditional investment banking businesses have been passed over. At
Lehman, the departing Mr Hill was known as a mergers and acquisitions
specialist.
Earlier this year, Mr John Mack was promoted from head of Morgan Stanley's
bond operations to president of the entire firm, leaving Mr Robert
Greenhill, the previous president, mergers and acquisitions veteran out in
the cold.
American Express yesterday announced that it would realise a first-quarter
after-tax gain of some Dollars 433m from the successful public offering of a
large part of its stake in First Data Corporation, which provides
information processing to the credit card industry.
The offering of 35.2m shares - 34.6m of them owned by American Express and
600,000 by the American Express Foundation - at a price of Dollars 32 a
share was announced at the start of this month.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Lehman Brothers.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6211 Security Brokers and Dealers.
