<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / International Company News: Delta Air Lines in move to lay
off 600 pilots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DELTA Air Lines, one of the 'big three' US carriers, yesterday announced
plans to lay off 600 pilots - the first temporary lay-offs of permanent
staff the carrier has implemented in 36 years. Delta sought to place the
lay-offs in the context of a 'fleet simplification' plan, although the move
also appeared to be a warning shot across the pilots' union's bows.
The plan, Delta said, would involve the retirement of 21 Airbus A310
aircraft which the company took over when it acquired assets - including
transatlantic routes - from the now-defunct Pan Am in 1991. However, Delta
would accept nine new A310s which it has on order, and the net loss of 12
A310s will help to accommodate a reduction in the carrier's transatlantic
schedules next autumn.
The carrier is also planning to retire 16 Boeing 727 aircraft, most of which
are employed on the east coast 'shuttle' routes. They will be replaced on
these routes by newer 727s, plucked from elsewhere in the domestic network.
The aircraft retirements represent a 3 per cent reduction in transatlantic
capacity, and a 1 per cent reduction for the group overall.
Delta said the moves made surplus 600 pilots, and said it planned to begin
laying off employees - on a last-in, first-out basis - from June.
Mr Ron Allen, Delta chairman, was quick to deny that the staff cutbacks were
related to the carrier's long-running dispute with the Air Line Pilots
Association. However, pilots are the only employees at Delta who are
unionised, and the only group which has stood out against the carrier's
recent request for wage cuts.
According to Delta, about 11 per cent of its pilots have offered to take pay
cuts, despite the fact that their union has not been able to agree terms on
a pay reduction package with management.
An application to start a new airline, called Friendship Airlines, was filed
with the US Department of Transportation yesterday. The carrier would be
headed by Mr Stephen Kolski, a former president of Continental Express, and
backed by Mr Frank Lorenzo, the controversial former owner of Continental.
Mr Lorenzo, who was renowned in the airline industry for his hard-nosed
labour tactics and reviled by the unions, would also be a director of the
new airline.
</TEXT>
