<HEADLINE>
FT  30 MAR 93 / International Company News: Euro Disney close to visitor
target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EURO DISNEY said yesterday it had come close to achieving its first-year
target of 11m visitors to its theme park, but that hotel occupancy and
spending per head were still below expectations.
Mr Philippe Bourguignon, who was appointed chairman last January, said the
company still expected to make a loss this year. Euro Disney made a pre-tax
loss of FFr339m (Dollars 60.3m) in the year to September 30 1992 and
announced a deficit of FFr492m for the first quarter of the current year.
However, Mr Steve Burke, executive vice-president, said, that the park would
achieve 11m visitors by the end of next month, only a few weeks after its
first anniversary on April 12. After a slow start, Euro Disney had been
expected to fall 500,000 visitors short of its first-year target.
Mr Burke said the improved attendance figures were the result of intensive
marketing in France, where interest in visiting the park had been below
expectations.
Analysts warned that the financial impact would be limited by discounted
tickets and the cost of extra staff to cope with the increase in visitors.
The company had offered residents of the Paris region 20 per cent to 30 per
cent discounts on entrance prices from January to the end of March. Even
more effective, Mr Burke said, were sales visits to companies and schools
throughout France.
Ms Rebecca Winnington-Ingram, European leisure analyst at Morgan Stanley in
London, revised her forecasts for Euro Disney's second-quarter loss to
FFr650m from FFr750m following yesterday's announcement. She expects Euro
Disney to produce a profit of FFr375m in the second half, reducing its total
loss to FFr769m in the full financial year to September 30.
Euro Disney's financial performance has been affected not only by its
initial operational difficulties, but also by unexpectedly high financing
costs. It has been hit by the rise in French interest rates and a shortfall
in capital gains.
</TEXT>
